body_text:
Although right triangles allow us to solve many applications, it is more common to find scenarios where the triangle we are interested in does not have a right angle. Two radar stations located 20 miles apart both detect a UFO located between them. The angle of elevatio n measured by the first station is 35 degrees. The angle of elevation measured by the second station is 15 degrees. What is the altitude of the UFO? We see that the triangle formed by the UFO and the two stations is not a right triangle. Of course, in any triangle we could draw an altitude, a perpendicular line from one vertex to the opposite side, forming two right triangles, but it would be nice to have methods for working directly with non-right triangles. In this section, we will expand upon the right triangle trigonometry we learned in Chapter 5, and adapt it to non-right triangles. Law of Sines Given an arbitrary non-right triangle, we can drop an altitude, which we temporarily label \(h\), to create two right triangles. Using the right triangle relationships, \[\sin (\alpha ) = \dfrac{h}{b}	ext{ and }\sin ( eta ) = \dfrac{h}{a}
onumber\] Solving both equations for \(h\), we get \(b\sin (\alpha ) = h\) and \(a\sin ( eta ) = h\). Since the \(h\) is the same in both equations, we establish \(b\sin (\alpha ) = a\sin ( eta )\). Dividing both sides by \(ab\), we conclude that \[\dfrac{\sin (\alpha )}{a} = \dfrac{\sin ( eta )}{b}
onumber\] Had we drawn the altitude to be perpendicular to side \(b\) or \(a\), we could similarly establish \[\dfrac{\sin (\alpha )}{a} = \dfrac{\sin (\gamma )}{c}	ext{ and }\dfrac{\sin ( eta )}{b} = \dfrac{\sin (\gamma )}{c}
onumber\] Collectively, these relationships are called the Law of Sines. LAW OF SINES Given a triangle with angles and sides opposite labeled as shown, the ratio of sine of angle to length of the opposite side will always be equal, or, symbolically, \[\dfrac{\sin (\alpha )}{a} = \dfrac{\sin ( eta )}{b} = \dfrac{\sin (\gamma )}{c}\] For clarity, we call side \(a\) the corresponding side of angle \(\alpha\). Similarly, we call angle \(\alpha\), the corresponding angle of side \(a\). Likewise for side \(b\) and angle \( eta\), and for side \(c\) and angle \(\gamma\). When we use the law of sines, we use any pair of ratios as an equation. In the most straightforward case, we know two angles and one of the corresponding sides. In addition to solving triangles in which two angles are known, the law of sines can be used to solve for an angle when two sides and one corresponding angle are known. Notice that in the problem above, when we use Law of Sines to solve for an unknown angle, there can be two possible solutions. This is called the ambiguous case, and can arise when we know two sides and a non-included angle. In the ambiguous case we may find that a particular set of given information can lead to 2, 1 or no solution at all. However, when an accurate picture of the triangle or suitable context is available, we can determine which angle is desired. Exercise \(\PageIndex{1}\) Given \(\alpha = 80^\circ ,a = 120,{m{ and }}b = 121\), find the corresponding and missing side and angles. If there is more than one possible solution, show both. Answer \[ rac{\sin (80^{\circ })}{120}= rac{\sin ( eta )}{121}
onumber\] \[1^{	ext{st}}	ext{ possible solution } egin{array}{l} eta = 83.2^\circ \\gamma = 16.8^\circ \c = 35.2\end{array}
onumber\] \[2^{	ext{nd}}	ext{ solution } egin{array}{l} eta = 96.8^\circ \\gamma = 3.2^\circ \c = 6.9\end{array}
onumber\] If we were given a picture of the triangle it may be possible to eliminate one of these Exercise \(\PageIndex{2}\) Given \(\alpha = 80^\circ ,a = 100,{m{ and }}b = 10\) find the missing side and angles. If there is more than one possible solution, show both. Answer \[\dfrac{\sin \left( {80^\circ } ight)}{120} = \dfrac{\sin \left(  eta ight)}{10}\quad  eta = 5.65^\circ 	ext{ or } eta = 174.35^\circ 
onumber\]; only the first is reasonable. \[\gamma = 180^\circ - 5.65^\circ - 80^\circ = 94.35^\circ 
onumber\] \[ rac{\sin (80^{\circ })}{120}= rac{\sin (94.35 ^{\circ })}{c}
onumber\] \[ eta = 5.65^\circ ,\gamma = 94.35^\circ ,c = 101.25
onumber\] Law of Cosines Suppose a boat leaves port, travels 10 miles, turns 20 degrees, and travels another 8 miles. How far from port is the boat? Unfortunately, while the Law of Sines lets us address many non-right triangle cases, it does not allow us to address triangles where the one known angle is included between two known sides, which means it is not a corresponding angle for a known side. For this, we need another tool. Given an arbitrary non-right triangle, we can drop an altitude, which we te mporarily label \(h\), to create two right triangles. We will divide the base \(b\) into two pieces, one of which we will temporarily label \(x\). From this picture, we can establish the right triangle relationship \[\cos (\alpha ) = \dfrac{x}{c}	ext{ or equivalently,} x = c\cos \left( \alpha ight)
onumber\] Using the Pythagorean Theorem, we can establish \[{\left( {b - x} ight)^2} + {h^2} = {a^2}	ext{ and }{x^2} + {h^2} = {c^2}
onumber\] Both of these equations can be solved for \({h^2}\) \[{h^2} = {a^2} - {\left( {b - x} ight)^2}	ext{ and }{h^2} = {c^2} - {x^2}
onumber\] Since the left side of each equation is \({h^2}\), the right sides must be equal \[{c^2} - {x^2} = {a^2} - {\left( {b - x} ight)^2}
onumber\]Multiply out the right \[{c^2} - {x^2} = {a^2} - \left( {b^2} - 2bx + {x^2} ight)
onumber\]Simplify \[{c^2} - {x^2} = {a^2} - {b^2} + 2bx - {x^2}
onumber\] \[{c^2} = {a^2} - {b^2} + 2bx
onumber\]Isolate \({a^2}\) \[{a^2} = {c^2} + {b^2} - 2bx
onumber\]Substitute in \(c\cos (\alpha ) = x\) from above \[{a^2} = {c^2} + {b^2} - 2bc\cos (\alpha )
onumber\] This result is called the Law of Cosines. Depending upon which side we dropped the altitude down from, we could have established this relationship using any of the angles. The important thing to note is that the right side of the equation involves an angle and the sides adjacent to that angle – the left side of the equation involves the side opposite that angle. LAW OF COSINES Given a triangle with angles and opposite sides labeled as shown, \[{a^2} = {c^2} + {b^2} - 2bc\cos (\alpha )\] \[{b^2} = {a^2} + {c^2} - 2ac\cos ( eta )\] \[{c^2} = {a^2} + {b^2} - 2ab\cos (\gamma )\] Notice that if one of the angles of the triangle is 90 degrees, cos(\(90^{circ}\)) = 0, so the formula \[{c^2} = {a^2} + {b^2} - 2ab\cos (90^\circ )
onumber\]Simplifies to \[{c^2} = {a^2} + {b^2}
onumber\] You should recognize this as the Pythagorean Theorem. Indeed, the Law of Cosines is sometimes called the Generalized Pythagorean Theorem , since it extends the Pythagorean Theorem to non-right triangles. In addition to solving for the missing side opposite one known angle, the Law of Cosines allows us to find the angles of a triangle when we know all three sides. Exercise \(\PageIndex{3}\) Given \(\alpha = 25^\circ ,b = 10,{m{ and }}c = 20\)find the missing side and angles. Answer \[{a^2} = {10^2} + {20^2} - 2(10)(20)\cos (25^\circ )\quad a = 11.725
onumber\] \[\dfrac{\sin \left( {25^\circ } ight)}{11.725} = \dfrac{\sin \left(  eta ight)}{10}\quad  eta = 21.1^\circ 	ext{ or } eta = 158.9^\circ 
onumber\] only the first is reasonable since 25° + 158.9° would exceed 180°. \[\gamma = 180^\circ - 21.1^\circ - 25^\circ = 133.9^\circ 
onumber\] \[ eta = 21.1^\circ , \gamma = 133.9^\circ , a = 11.725
onumber\] Notice that since the inverse cosine can return any angle between 0 and 180 degrees, there will not be any ambiguous cases when using Law of Cosines to find an angle. Important Topics of This Section Law of Sines Solving for sides Solving for angles Ambiguous case, 0, 1 or 2 solutions Law of Cosines Solving for sides Solving for angles Generalized Pythagorean Theorem

examples.text:
Example \(\PageIndex{1}\) In the triangle shown here, solve for the unknown sides and angle. Solution Solving for the unknown angle is relatively easy, since the three angles must add to 180 degrees. From this, we can determine that \[\gamma = 180^{\circ} - 50^{\circ} - 30^{\circ} = 100^{\circ}
onumber\] To find an unknown side, we need to know the corresponding angle, and we also need another known ratio. Since we know the angle \(50^{\circ}\) and its corresponding side, we can use this for one of the two ratios. To look for side \(b\), we would use its corresponding angle, \(30^{\circ}\). \[\dfrac{\sin (50^\circ )}{10} = \dfrac{\sin (30^\circ )}{b}
onumber\]Multiply both sides by \(b\) \[b\dfrac{\sin (50^\circ )}{10} = \sin (30^\circ )
onumber\]Divide, or multiply by the reciprocal, to solve for \(b\) \[b = \sin (30^\circ )\dfrac{10}{\sin (50^\circ )} \approx 6.527
onumber\] Similarly, to solve for side \(c\), we set up the equation \[\dfrac{\sin (50^\circ )}{10} = \dfrac{\sin (100^\circ )}{c}
onumber\] \[c = \sin (100^\circ )\dfrac{10}{\sin (50^\circ )} \approx 12.856
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{7}\) Find the unknown side and angles of this triangle. Solution Notice that we don’t have both pieces of any side/angle pair, so the Law of Sines would not work with this triangle. Since we have the angle included between the two known sides, we can turn to Law of Cosines. Since the left side of any of the Law of Cosines equations involves the side opposite the known angle, the left side in this situation will involve the side x. The other two sides can be used in either order. \[{x^2} = {10^2} + {12^2} - 2(10)(12)\cos (30^\circ )
onumber\]Evaluate the cosine \[{x^2} = {10^2} + {12^2} - 2(10)(12)\dfrac{\sqrt 3 }{2}
onumber\]Simplify \[{x^2} = 244 - 120\sqrt 3 
onumber\]Take the square root \[x = \sqrt {244 - 120\sqrt 3 } \approx 6.013
onumber\] Now that we know an angle and its corresponding side, we can use the Law of Sines to fill in the remaining angles of the triangle. Solving for angle \(	heta\), \[\dfrac{\sin (30^\circ )}{6.013} = \dfrac{\sin (	heta )}{10}
onumber\] \[\sin (	heta ) = \dfrac{10\sin (30^\circ )}{6.013}
onumber\]Use the inverse sine \[	heta = {\sin ^{ - 1}}\left( \dfrac{10\sin (30^\circ )}{6.013} ight) \approx 56.256^\circ 
onumber\] The other possibility for \(	heta\) would be \(	heta = 180^{\circ} – 56.256^{\circ} = 123.744^{\circ}\). In the original picture, \(	heta\) is an acute angle, so 123.744°\(^{\circ}\) doesn’t make sense if we assume the picture is drawn to scale. Proceeding with \(	heta = 56.256^{\circ}\), we can then find the third angle of the triangle: \[\phi = 180^\circ - 30^\circ - 56.256^\circ = 93.744^\circ 
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{10}\) To measure the height of a hill, a woman measures the angle of elevation to the top of the hill to be 24 degrees. She then moves back 200 feet and measures the angle of elevation to be 22 degrees. Find the height of the hill. Solution As with many problems of this nature, it will be helpful to draw a picture. Notice there are three triangles formed here – the right triangle including the height \(h\) and the 22 degree angle, the right triangle including the height \(h\) and the 24 degree angle, and the (non-right) obtuse triangle including the 200 ft side. Since this is the triangle we have the most information for, we will begin with it. It may seem odd to work with this triangle since it does not include the desired side \(h\), but we don’t have enough information to work with either of the right triangles yet. We can find the obtuse angle of the triangle, since it and the angle of 24 degrees complete a straight line – a 180 degree angle. The obtuse angle must be \(180^{\circ} - 24^{\circ} = 156^{\circ}\). From this, we can determine that the third angle is \(2^{\circ}\). We know one side is 200 feet, and its corresponding angle is \(2^{\circ}\), so by introducing a temporary variable \(x\) for one of the other sides (as shown below), we can use Law of Sines to solve for this length \(x\). \[\dfrac{x}{\sin (22^\circ )} = \dfrac{200}{\sin (2^\circ )}
onumber\]Setting up the Law of Sines \[x = \sin (22^\circ )\dfrac{200}{\sin (2^\circ )}
onumber\]isolating the \(x\) value \[x = 2146.77	ext{ ft}
onumber\] Now that we know \(x\), we can use right triangle properties to solve for \(h\). \[\sin (24^\circ ) = \dfrac{m{opposite}}{m{hypotenuse}} = \dfrac{h}{x} = \dfrac{h}{2146.77}
onumber\] \[h = 2146.77\sin (24^\circ ) = 873.17	ext{ ft}
onumber\] The hill is 873 feet high.

